<br>
1. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Lull Resists</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->    (helps determine if you aggro or not)<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4882">eq.crgaming.com/viewartic...ticle=4882</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Is the effect resisted? <br>
<br>
If the effect is resisted, will the NPC get angry and tell its friends that it's time for a BardSnack(tm), or will it ignore what just happened? <br>
<br>
Charisma is the sole determinant in the second check. It doesn't affect (resists). <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
2. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Charm</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/archives.asp?Day=8&Month=10&Year=1999&ID=4660&Action=View">eq.crgaming.com/archives....ction=View</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
I checked with GZ this morning regardng the effect Charisma has in charming. The answer is that its effect is twofold. <br>
Firstly it effects the chance at resisting the initial charm cast. Secondly, and more importantly, it makes it harder for the charmed NPC's save to successfully roll. This basically means it does effect duration. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
3.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Mez and Blur</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/archives.asp?Day=10&Month=11&Year=1999&ID=431&Action=View">eq.crgaming.com/archives....ction=View</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Spoke with GZ this morning regarding Charisma and its effect in relation to resists. <br>
<br>
In summary Charisma effects the resists of Charms, Mesmerises and Blur-Type Spells across all classes.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Boston Fanfaire<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4451">eq.crgaming.com/viewartic...ticle=4451</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Is Charisma actually taken into account on mesmerizations and charms?<br>
<br>
Yes it is.  It varies on a number of spells to its actual usefulness but it does have a use.  There are different levels of charisma for different classes.  The system does take into account that an Enchanter should have a higher charisma than say a Necromancer.  It’s unfair to expect masters of the undead to be entirely charismatic.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
GZ ON CHARISMA (SOFT) CAP<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/archives.asp?Day=19&Month=1&Year=2000&ID=675&Action=View">eq.crgaming.com/archives....ction=View</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>GZ confirmed that the soft cap on Charisma is 200</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
For those unfamiliar with how a soft cap works, once a stat goes over 200 the actual real benefit diminishes. In practical terms this means an increase of a stat from 190 to 200 gives greater benefit than increasing it from 200 to 210. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
GZ = Geoffrey Zatkin <br>
<br>
